    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "Acute angle-closure glaucoma is an OPHTHALMOLOGIC EMERGENCY — permanent vision loss within hours if untreated",
      "Classic presentation: painful red eye + blurred vision + halos + nausea/vomiting + mid-dilated fixed pupil + hazy cornea",
      "IOP measurement (tonometry) is diagnostic — normal is 10-21 mmHg; in AACG typically 40-80+ mmHg",
      "Immediate treatment: topical timolol 0.5% + pilocarpine 2% + topical prednisolone + IV acetazolamide 500mg + IV mannitol if refractory",
      "Pilocarpine constricts the pupil and pulls the iris away from the drainage angle — but may not work until IOP is lowered first",
      "Definitive treatment: laser peripheral iridotomy (LPI) — must be performed within 24-48 hours by ophthalmology"
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Retrobulbar hemorrhage (trauma + proptosis + vision loss — lateral canthotomy)",
      "Acute anterior uveitis/iritis (photophobia, small pupil — opposite of AACG)",
      "Endophthalmitis (post-surgical or endogenous — hypopyon, severe)",
      "Orbital cellulitis (periorbital swelling, proptosis, pain with eye movement, fever)",
      "Temporal arteritis / GCA (age >50, headache, jaw claudication, vision loss — check ESR/CRP)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Diagnosing 'migraine with nausea' without examining the eye — AACG causes headache and vomiting",
      "Not checking pupil response and corneal clarity — mid-dilated fixed pupil + hazy cornea is pathognomonic",
      "Not measuring IOP — this is the confirmatory test (most EDs have Tono-Pen or iCare tonometer)",
      "Giving anticholinergics for nausea (ondansetron is fine, but avoid promethazine which can worsen angle closure)",
      "Not treating the fellow eye prophylactically — if one eye is susceptible, the other usually is too",
      "Delaying ophthalmology consultation — needs laser iridotomy within 24-48 hours"
    ],
