    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "The 6 P's of acute limb ischemia: Pain, Pallor, Pulselessness, Poikilothermia (cold), Paresthesia, Paralysis — motor deficit is a LATE and ominous sign",
      "Rutherford classification: I (viable), IIa (marginally threatened — sensory loss, salvageable with prompt treatment), IIb (immediately threatened — motor loss, requires emergent intervention), III (irreversible — mottled, no Doppler signal, amputation)",
      "This patient is Rutherford IIa progressing to IIb — URGENT revascularization within 6 hours",
      "Embolic vs. thrombotic: sudden onset with no prior claudication + AFib + 'meniscus sign' on CTA = embolic. Thrombotic typically has chronic PAD history with gradual worsening.",
      "Treatment options: surgical embolectomy (Fogarty catheter), catheter-directed thrombolysis, or hybrid approach",
      "HIT HISTORY in this patient — CANNOT use unfractionated heparin. Use argatroban or bivalirudin for anticoagulation."
    ],
