    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "Acute pancreatitis diagnosis: 2 of 3 criteria — (1) characteristic epigastric pain radiating to back, (2) lipase >3x ULN, (3) imaging findings",
      "GALLSTONE pancreatitis: ALT >150 U/L predicts gallstone etiology with >85% PPV. CBD dilation and jaundice confirm.",
      "Necrotizing pancreatitis (>30% glandular non-enhancement on contrast CT) has mortality of 15-30% — requires ICU admission",
      "Aggressive IV fluid resuscitation is cornerstone of early management — Lactated Ringer's preferred, goal-directed (target UOP >0.5mL/kg/hr, trending Hct and BUN)",
      "ERCP indicated URGENTLY (<24 hours) for gallstone pancreatitis with ongoing biliary obstruction (jaundice, dilated CBD, cholangitis)",
      "Severity scoring: BISAP (at admission), Ranson criteria (0h and 48h), APACHE II, CT Severity Index — all predict complications and mortality"
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Cholangitis (fever + jaundice + RUQ pain = Charcot triad → ERCP urgently. Add hypotension + AMS = Reynold pentad → emergent ERCP)",
      "Necrotizing pancreatitis (contrast-enhanced CT at 72 hours is optimal timing for assessing necrosis extent)",
      "Infected pancreatic necrosis (fever + worsening after initial improvement, typically >7-10 days — CT-guided aspiration, antibiotics, possible necrosectomy)",
      "Abdominal compartment syndrome (massive fluid resuscitation + inflammation → check bladder pressure if abdomen becomes tense)",
      "Organ failure (pulmonary, renal, cardiovascular — Modified Marshall score to assess)",
      "Pseudocyst/Walled-Off Necrosis (late complications — weeks to months)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Under-resuscitating with IV fluids — these patients third-space massive volumes; aggressive early IVF reduces complications",
      "Ordering CT too early — contrast-enhanced CT at <72 hours may underestimate necrosis. Initial diagnosis is clinical + lipase.",
      "Not recognizing gallstone etiology — check ALT, bilirubin, alkaline phosphatase, RUQ ultrasound on ALL pancreatitis patients",
      "Feeding too late — early enteral nutrition (within 24 hours if tolerated, nasojejunal if needed) improves outcomes. NPO only if actively vomiting.",
      "Giving prophylactic antibiotics for necrotizing pancreatitis — NOT recommended unless infected necrosis suspected (sterile necrosis is managed without antibiotics)",
      "Not performing cholecystectomy before discharge — recurrent gallstone pancreatitis rate is 25-30% within 6 weeks if gallbladder is left in place"
    ],
