          "teaching": "Topical corticosteroid eye drops are highly effective for acute severe allergic conjunctivitis flares but carry significant long-term risks: corticosteroid-induced glaucoma (irreversible optic nerve damage) and posterior subcapsular cataracts occur with prolonged use, even with low-potency preparations. They must only be prescribed and monitored by ophthalmology with regular IOP checks and slit-lamp examinations — never for unsupervised long-term use.",
